Here are some of the latest updates: Former Australian prime minister Scott Morrison has joined Boris Johnson on a trip to Israel Israeli warplanes have struck two refugee camps, killing at least 53 people and wounding dozens, according to Gaza's health ministry Efforts are underway to resume evacuations of injured Gazans and foreign nationals from the region after a deadly attack on an ambulance according to Egyptian, US and Qatari officials Palestinian authority tells US Secretary of State Antony Blinken there must be an "immediate ceasefire" Pope Francis makes an urgent plea for a halt to the conflict
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Welcome to today's live coverage

children.content: Good morning, welcome to today's live coverage of the Israel-Gaza war.
Here are some of the latest updates:
Former Australian prime minister Scott Morrison has joined Boris Johnson on a trip to Israel
Israeli warplanes have struck two refugee camps, killing at least 53 people and wounding dozens, according to Gaza's health ministry
Efforts are underway to resume evacuations of injured Gazans and foreign nationals from the region after a deadly attack on an ambulance according to Egyptian, US and Qatari officials
Palestinian authority tells US Secretary of State Antony Blinken there must be an "immediate ceasefire"
Pope Francis makes an urgent plea for a halt to the conflict

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli warplanes have struck two refugee camps, killing at least 53 people and wounding dozens, according to Gaza's health ministry. At the Maghazi refugee camp in Gaza, people searched for bodies or survivors. "All night I and the other men were trying to pick the dead from the rubble. We got children, dismembered, torn-apart flesh," said Saeed al-Nejma, 53, adding that he had been asleep with his family when the blast hit his neighbourhood. The camp had been struck overnight, killing at least 45, health officials said. Hamas said in a statement posted on Telegram that Israel had "directly" bombed citizens' homes, adding that most of the dead were women and children. Israel Defense Forces said it was gathering details about this incident. Hospital workers said Israeli jets also struck a house near a school at the crowded Bureij refugee camp, killing at least 13 people. The Bureij refugee camp is home to an estimated 46,000 people.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel strikes two refugee camps, Gaza authorities say

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Twelve more Australians who fled Gaza have arrived on a flight in Sydney last night. The passengers are the biggest group of repatriated Australians from Gaza to land back in the country on a single commercial flight. Over the weekend a family of four also landed in Adelaide and another family of three touched down in Melbourne. ABC News was at the airport last night, where some said they were extremely happy and relieved to be home. Others spoke about the horror and trauma their family and friends are still facing in Gaza. The Department of Foreign Affairs says that they have now helped about 25 Australians and their family members leave Gaza, and they're still trying to help evacuate a further 67 Australian citizens and their family members.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Twelve more Australians arrive home from Gaza
